   <mods:abstract>As a part of the developing scholarship in childhood studies, propaganda studies, Cold War China, and transwar studies of World War II history, this project examines the changing propagandistic themes that informed Chinese role-playing games, from fighting demon-like Japanese enemies in the 1960s to enjoying playful Japanese opponents in the 2010s. By surveying the role real children and players played in reshaping China's memories of the Fifteen Years War (1931- 1945), this dissertation aims to understand the interactions between children and states, propaganda and reality, identity and memory, as well as games and grand strategy presented with children's images and actual children's experiences with playthings. Based on primary sources from official Chinese propaganda channels toward children in the People's Republic of China (PRC), such as New Year's paintings, posters, broadcasts, youth newspapers, magazines, and Chinese children's publications in these channels, this project argues that Chinese children have been playing active roles in shaping Chinese propaganda throughout the history of the PRC. By focusing on children's own experiences and their own voices, this dissertation attempts to recenter the essential roles Chinese children played not only in the Fifteen Years War but also in the continuing Communist effort to maintain China's revolutionary fervor during the Cold War era and beyond.</mods:abstract>
